latestPosts.caption:
Hope you're having a wonderful Tuesday ✨

Sharing my outfit formula of the day! I've been wearing a lot more colours lately. Maybe I'm being influenced by some of the amazing accounts I follow who are truly magicians when it comes to combining colours or maybe it's my Pinterest board.

There's so many beautiful Pantone colour combinations that keep getting suggested on Pinterest and honestly, they make these rainy days that much more joyful.

Do you like wearing bright colours?

A quick outfit formula of the day. 

The weekend is a great time to style pieces you're not that comfortable wearing on a daily basis yet.

That's this tie for me. I've had it for over a month and I still haven't worn it out.

Thought today was a great day to style it and wear it on the family get-together for Father's day. 

I'm still not 100% sure it is my style, but I'm glad I ended up wearing it.

Hope you are having a wonderful Sunday ✨

We are ringing in the weekend with a lovely shade of pink: Pantone's Pink-a-boo 🩷

I found this men's shirt a couple of months ago while thrifting. Since I'm used to mostly wearing neutrals, I thought it would be fun to spice things up a bit, so we are creating colourful outfits! 

Turns out, this shade of light pink is far more versatile than I thought it would be. 

Which one of these combinations is your favourite? 

Hope you have a wonderful weekend ahead ✨

#stylingpink #pinkshirt #oldmoneyaesthetic #classicstyle #parisianstyle

✨ Hope you're having a lovely Wednesday

I'm wearing a linen blend dress from @commense.official, as well as a cute little bag from the same brand.

The heels are from @vivaia_official and are the most comfortable heels I own.

All these pieces were previously gifted ✨

Hope you're having a wonderful start of the new week ✨

These type of weaving methods were normally reserved for the nobility, until Joseph Marie Jacquard invented the Jacquard loom in France in 1803, making these fabrics reach a wider audience. 

The Jacquard loom is used on fabric to interweave the pattern directly into the material. This is achieved with punch cards that control the weaving patterns. 

The concept of using coded instructions (the punch cards) to automate a machine, was hereby born. Later, these punch cards served as inspiration for the creation of early computers (Babbage engines f.e.). 

To say I'm intrigued is an understatement, making this vintage Jacquard blouse made in France, all the more special. Highly recommend watching a video to see this weaving method in action.

latestPosts.caption:
What are some things that get heavily promoted, but you don't agree with?

Social media can be a lot, the constant push for products. Be it makeup, skincare, clothes. Makes us believe we don't have enough. That we need all of these things to be happier. It's an endless loop and honestly, it is so silly.

True happiness comes from within and you won't be able to fine tune your skincare routine, your makeup or your style if you constantly add more products.

The magic happens when you finally start playing around with what you have. When you start noticing what actually suits YOU the best and not some influencer.

Everything you buy, should be attuned to your own characteristics and what you love.

Also, as a chronic people pleaser - I can't stress enough how important it is to put up boundaries. It is not your responsibility to make everyone feel good and at ease. You should focus on you and your mental health 👏🏻

Hope you're having a lovely Tuesday and if you made it this far - thank you so much.

Also - the visuals aren't from today. It's a miserable, rainy, grey day over here 😁

✨ Hope you're having a lovely Sunday

Wanted to make a fun little reel about thrifting.

There's so many reasons why I started thrifting a couple of years ago, some of these are:

- seeing how young women get abused and taken advantage of making clothes

- appreciating natural fabrics

- appreciating good quality garments

- knowing how polluting the fashion industry can be

- trying to figure out my personal style 

Clothes being more expensive doesn't necessarily mean they are great quality or that the working conditions of the people making them are good.

So, whenever I can, I try to thrift first. 

For anyone interested - I didn't end up buying the sleeveless shirt. My collection of shirts is vast enough at this point 🤭

The last photo is the reality of taking photos outside 😁

I'm wearing :
- very old top
- thrifted pleated trousers
- @massimodutti belt 
- @berlinerbags leather bag (gifted last year) 
- @veja sneakers 

Hope you're having a wonderful Saturday ✨
